Prosper Loan Data¶

by Abanoub Aziz¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

  • This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others supplied by a credit company called Propser. Prosper or Prosper Marketplace Inc. is a San Francisco, California based company specializing in loans at low interest rates to the borrowers.
  • This data dictionary explains the variables in the data set.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The orinigal dataset containted 113937 rows of data, and after filtering the dataset and performing initial wrangling, the resulting dataset contains 84853 rows of data for the following variables:

Term, LoanStatus, BorrowerRate, ProsperRating (Alpha), ProsperScore, ListingCategory (numeric), BorrowerState, EmploymentStatus, DelinquenciesLast7Years, StatedMonthlyIncome, LoanOriginalAmount, LoanOriginationDate

Most of the variables we are intrested in are in numeric format with the exception of the following:

LoanStatus, ProsperRating (Alpha), BorrowerState, EmploymentStatus and LoanOriginationDate

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of intrest in this datset is the Loan Status and what is the effect of the chosen variables on the status of the loan.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

After an initial investigation of the data set via the data dictionary, I have came to the conclusion that the PropserRating/Score with the EmployementStatus, LoanOriginalAmount and DelinquinciesLast7Years are the most important factors in determining what is likely to happen with the Loan Status

# We will start by checking the main variable in question, the "LoanStatus"
# By using the value_counts method to soirt the values in descending order of count we can then use the index method to return
# A series with the descending order of the LoanStatus and order the Bar Chart using that
# Finally by using a for loop we can have the count of the values appear as text on top of the each bar 

freq_status = df_sub['LoanStatus'].value_counts()
status_order = freq_status.index
plt.figure(figsize=[16, 8])
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
sb.countplot(data = df_sub, x = 'LoanStatus', color = base_color, order = status_order);
for i in range (freq_status.shape[0]):
    count = freq_status[i]
    plt.text(i, count+2000, count, ha = 'center', va='top')

It seems that most of the loans in this dataset are current, followed completed, followed by chargedoff, followed by an insiginat number of Defaulted loans, the the remaining LoanStatus values being occuring less than a 1000 times.

In [25]:
# First we need to calculate the mean and standard deviations of the "StatedMonthlyIncome" variable

income_mean = df_sub.StatedMonthlyIncome.mean()
income_std = df_sub.StatedMonthlyIncome.std()

# Since we're limiting our view 3 standard deviations of the mean, we are going to calculate it using by the following

income_max = income_mean + 3*income_std
In [26]:
# Finally we are going to draw the graph using the view calculated before

plt.figure(figsize = [16, 8])

plt.xlim(0, income_max);

It seems that our data is still right skewed, however this view allows us to see the actual data. Here I have chosen a bin size of 1000, and it seems that the most common StatedMonthlyIncome is around 5000, from here it seems that the outliers are simply errors in the data which we will eliminate before starting the bivariate exploration

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The most intresting variable here would be the loan status, it seems that most of the loans are currents with a very small number of defaulted loans. The next intresting variable here would be the ProsperRating and the ProsperScore valiable and those seem to be normally distrubted which is to be expected. The existence of extreme outliers in the StatedMonthlyIncome seems to indicate that there are erroneous datapoints in the dataset no transformation will be needed here since it's a data error and is to be removed. Intrestgly the most common state where customer took out loans happens to be CA, NY, TX and FL where CA and NY can be explained by the fact that they are the 2nd and 3rd most expensive states in terms of living expenses in the US.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The only usual distrubtion came about from the StatedMonthlyIncome variable and that was resovled by removing the erroneous datapoints, the second step done to clean the data for further investigation is to only consider loans that are not current, since we don't know the results of the loan (whether it will default or complete)

# Ploting the graph again using the filtered data and creating a function to write the proportion percentage on top of each bar

def print_proportion(plot, x, y):
    """Function to write the proportion percentage on top of each bar on the countplot graphs,
    x values needs to be in decending order for the function to work correctly,
    plot is the name of the graph variable, 
    x is the variable that we are categorizing for in the x axis,
    y is the variable that we are categorizing for in the y axis (count)"""
    # using the patches method to split each bar, then using get_height() to get the height of each bar
    a = [p.get_height() for p in plot.patches] 
    patch = [p for p in plot.patches] # Split each bar into it's own "patch"
    for i in range(x.nunique()): # loops for the number of values in the x axis
        total = x.value_counts().values[i] # Finds the total for all each x value
        for j in range(y.nunique()): # loops for the number of values in the y axis
            # Find the proportion for each bar up to 1 decimalplace
            proportion = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * a[(j*x.nunique() + i)]/total)
            # The X position formula for each proportion percentage 
            x_pos = patch[(j*x.nunique() + i)].get_x() + patch[(j*x.nunique() + i)].get_width()/ 2 - 0.05
            # The Y position formula for each proportion percentage
            y_pos = patch[(j*x.nunique() + i)].get_y() + patch[(j*x.nunique() + i)].get_height()+ 100
            # Draw the text on top of each bar using the proportion x_pos and y_pos
            ax.annotate(proportion, (x_pos, y_pos), size = 12)

plt.figure(figsize = [16, 8])
ax = sb.countplot(data = df_sub3 , x = 'LoanStatus', hue = 'ListingCategory', palette = 'mako',
                  order = df_sub3['LoanStatus'].value_counts().index)
legend_labels, _= ax.get_legend_handles_labels()

print_proportion(ax, df_sub3['LoanStatus'], df_sub3['ListingCategory'])

def mapsize(g, x, y):
    """Function to change the width, height for a plot where g is the plot, x is the width and y is the height"""
    g.fig.set_figwidth(x);
    g.fig.set_figheight(y);
